WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.420
So, I'm here to talk about conformal inference and how to do that in tidymodels.

00:00:11.420 --> 00:00:14.800
Conformal inference, you put those two words together and if you would ask me maybe like

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:18.799
a year ago what they mean, I'd essentially be like, I don't know.

00:00:18.799 --> 00:00:24.440
So you know, it's kind of like an oddly named technique, so in hindsight maybe a better

00:00:24.440 --> 00:00:30.160
title for this presentation was how you can make prediction intervals for any type of

00:00:30.160 --> 00:00:35.880
model without making very much statistical assumptions about your data or your model.

00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:40.380
Just to remind you, if you want to put in some questions, here's the link for it.

00:00:40.380 --> 00:00:45.599
And also in this wee tiny little font down here, you can see the link to the slides if

00:00:45.599 --> 00:00:46.599
you want them.

00:00:46.599 --> 00:00:50.720
All right, so maybe I should start first by saying, well, what's a prediction interval

00:00:50.720 --> 00:00:52.080
if you've never heard of that?

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:54.880
And so a prediction interval, it's like a confidence interval, but it's an interval

00:00:54.880 --> 00:00:58.439
on a separate type of object.

00:00:58.439 --> 00:01:03.200
If you had like a 95% prediction interval, that means that you have a bounds where 95%

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:08.919
of the time a new observation that you would acquire later will fall into that interval.

00:01:08.919 --> 00:01:12.800
So whereas confidence intervals are on like the mean prediction, this is about new observations.

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:18.160
And the little diagram here shows you both confidence interval, which is kind of very

00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:21.400
narrow for this data set, and a wider prediction interval.

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:24.720
And you can see there's a couple of data points on the bottom and a few on the top that don't

00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:25.720
fall in.

00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:30.080
So I think that's a 95% interval right there.

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:34.680
People use these when they can get them, which is not that often for models.

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:38.839
It gives you a sense of uncertainty about your prediction usually.

00:01:38.839 --> 00:01:44.680
So it gives you a sense of how much should I not trust the prediction, but you can sort

00:01:44.680 --> 00:01:48.480
of calibrate your expectations as to how good the prediction is.

00:01:49.480 --> 00:01:52.839
All right, so let's start with just some data, right?

00:01:52.839 --> 00:01:56.239
So this is just like a histogram on its side.

00:01:56.239 --> 00:01:57.239
It's 500 data points.

00:01:57.239 --> 00:02:03.199
It's centered around zero, maybe like plus or minus like, I don't know, 0.15.

00:02:03.199 --> 00:02:08.600
And so you spend some time collecting this data, and then you get the 501st data point,

00:02:08.600 --> 00:02:10.000
and let's say it falls down here.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.639
And it's like, well, it's not outside the range per se, but is that like a new data

00:02:14.639 --> 00:02:18.479
point from the same distribution, or has something changed, like the model drift question

00:02:18.479 --> 00:02:20.919
and things like that?

00:02:20.919 --> 00:02:25.399
And so what we can do is, if we were from a statistical standpoint, if we want to make

00:02:25.399 --> 00:02:29.800
some sort of judgment about whether this new data point is from our original distribution,

00:02:29.800 --> 00:02:33.179
one thing we could do is use good old-fashioned quantiles.

00:02:33.179 --> 00:02:37.880
So if you wanted to do like, let's say you wanted a 9% interval, what you could do is

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:43.199
get the 0.05 quantile on the lower end and the 95% quantile.

00:02:43.199 --> 00:02:50.160
And if you were to make a completely distribution-free probabilistic statement about that, you could

00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:54.399
say that 90% of the time, when I get data from this distribution, they're going to fall

00:02:54.399 --> 00:02:56.199
in between that interval.

00:02:56.199 --> 00:02:59.080
And so this is where the conformal part comes in.

00:02:59.080 --> 00:03:02.679
So you would say that that new data point, if it fell within that interval, it conforms

00:03:02.679 --> 00:03:06.720
to sort of this original reference distribution here.

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:10.800
So if you were to take this data set, compute those particular intervals, so there's a lower

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:16.119
95%, and this is like the 95% interval quantile, and you would think that any new data point

00:03:16.119 --> 00:03:20.360
that falls in here would be consistent with the original data.

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:23.720
And you can see, of course, there's false positives, 5% of the time here and 5% of the

00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:24.720
time up here.

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:28.279
In this particular data point, you would not really consider to be consistent with the

00:03:28.279 --> 00:03:29.880
original data.

00:03:29.880 --> 00:03:31.600
So why am I telling you this?

00:03:31.600 --> 00:03:35.320
Like suppose instead of me just saying we have some data, let's say they were out-of-sample

00:03:35.320 --> 00:03:36.440
residuals.

00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:39.960
So let's say you fit some sort of regression model, you had an extra data set, you know,

00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:44.679
just laying around like we do all the time, and you took that model and you predict on

00:03:44.679 --> 00:03:47.839
this different data set, you can compute those residuals.

00:03:47.839 --> 00:03:52.559
And so that gives you a sense of, for the data that was collected, especially in what

00:03:52.559 --> 00:03:56.720
we call this the calibration data set, you could say like, on average, this is what I

00:03:56.720 --> 00:04:02.639
expected the noise around my predicted values to be based on these residuals.

00:04:02.639 --> 00:04:08.520
So if this is a training set, and this is just a nonlinear function I fit to it, we

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:12.839
build the model on this data set, we take that same model fit to the calibration data

00:04:12.839 --> 00:04:16.279
set, this 500 I just showed you, and calculate the residuals.

00:04:16.279 --> 00:04:19.079
And that generates this histogram that I just showed you.

00:04:19.079 --> 00:04:24.760
And then what we can do is we can take this zero-centered histogram and basically center

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:27.399
it around the predicted values of our model.

00:04:27.399 --> 00:04:31.679
So this is like a test set, so we get new data points, we, you know, the same model

00:04:31.679 --> 00:04:32.679
fit here.

00:04:32.679 --> 00:04:36.239
Oh, and by the way, I swear to God, it's completely accidental that these colors match the ones

00:04:36.239 --> 00:04:37.239
of our T-shirts.

00:04:37.320 --> 00:04:42.399
I didn't realize until like an hour ago, I was like, oof, it's not like me.

00:04:42.399 --> 00:04:49.239
So anyway, so these are like the, it's a consistently, consistent-width band around the predicted

00:04:49.239 --> 00:04:52.679
values in here, and I guess we're calling that purple.

00:04:52.679 --> 00:04:57.119
And you can see some of the data points don't fall inside the band, but mostly they do.

00:04:57.119 --> 00:05:00.959
And this is basically something akin to a prediction interval, it's just going about

00:05:00.959 --> 00:05:03.480
it in a completely different way.

00:05:03.480 --> 00:05:07.720
Those prediction intervals are what we call parametric, we have to make some sort of statistical

00:05:07.720 --> 00:05:12.679
or probabilistic assumption about your data and the model and things like that.

00:05:12.679 --> 00:05:18.119
So what we tend to think of when we do these conformal intervals is that they have, if

00:05:18.119 --> 00:05:22.519
it were like a typical prediction interval you get from just straight-up linear regression,

00:05:22.519 --> 00:05:27.359
we'd say that, you know, a particular data point has a coverage of, let's say, 95%.

00:05:27.359 --> 00:05:32.519
But in this case, what we would say is, on average, across all the samples that we use,

00:05:32.559 --> 00:05:35.799
the coverage for that interval is 95%.

00:05:35.799 --> 00:05:42.440
So it's really the additional bit here is average, usually, for most conformal methods

00:05:42.440 --> 00:05:43.440
at least.

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:48.279
So if you're a statistician or something like that, and you're interested in the methodology,

00:05:48.279 --> 00:05:52.959
there's been quite a lot written about this, especially lately, it's been kind of exploding

00:05:52.959 --> 00:05:56.880
both in terms of papers and in terms of visibility.

00:05:56.880 --> 00:06:01.880
It has a very strong frequentist theme to it, if you know what that means.

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:07.200
We're basically using quantiles and empirical distributions, and it's sort of, when you

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:11.000
read about this, it really sort of kind of ties in in an indirect way to what we would

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:13.239
call non-parametric inference.

00:06:13.239 --> 00:06:17.160
So anyway, so that's all well and good.

00:06:17.160 --> 00:06:18.160
So what's good about it?

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:22.760
Well, they make very, these intervals require very, very minimal assumptions about your

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:23.760
data.

00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:29.399
Exchangeable data means that if I just reorder the data, you know, I can get the same results.

00:06:29.399 --> 00:06:32.760
And that's not true for time series, but it's generally true for a lot of other situations.

00:06:32.760 --> 00:06:37.239
And of course, time series are important, so there are specialized conformal methods

00:06:37.239 --> 00:06:39.320
that are related to time series.

00:06:39.320 --> 00:06:42.839
Matt D'Ancia's model time package has those in them, so you can get those if that's your

00:06:42.839 --> 00:06:43.839
thing.

00:06:43.839 --> 00:06:47.359
It can work with any type of regression or classification model.

00:06:47.359 --> 00:06:50.959
But so far in the probably package, I've only implemented it for regression.

00:06:50.959 --> 00:06:52.480
So we're working on that.

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:53.799
And it's relatively fast.

00:06:53.799 --> 00:06:56.000
There's a couple of different methods I'll show you.

00:06:56.040 --> 00:06:59.760
The ones I'll show you are all, you know, relatively fast to both train the conformal

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:03.600
interval method and to make new predictions.

00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:07.119
There's one called full conformal, which is the one that honestly kind of makes the most

00:07:07.119 --> 00:07:10.600
sense to me how this thing works, but it's abominably slow.

00:07:10.600 --> 00:07:15.359
So we have that in tiny models, but like, you probably don't want to do that.

00:07:15.359 --> 00:07:21.040
Anyway, the cons is because it doesn't really make any, you know, it's making minimal assumptions.

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:24.899
And as you'll see in a little bit, they don't necessarily extrapolate well.

00:07:24.899 --> 00:07:28.660
So if you're making a prediction on a new sample and it falls well outside of your training

00:07:28.660 --> 00:07:34.859
or calibration set, the coverage of that or even the interval itself may not be very good.

00:07:34.859 --> 00:07:37.899
And so, you know, that's a little bit different than what we would see in things like linear

00:07:37.899 --> 00:07:38.899
regression.

00:07:38.899 --> 00:07:42.980
Let's see what else.

00:07:42.980 --> 00:07:46.140
So if that's a problem, if you're not sure, you might be saying to yourself, well, how

00:07:46.140 --> 00:07:49.459
am I going to know if I'm really extrapolating if I have a bunch of predictors?

00:07:49.459 --> 00:07:51.540
We do have something called the applicable package.

00:07:51.700 --> 00:07:55.579
It was generated by one of our interns, Marley, a couple of years ago.

00:07:55.579 --> 00:07:59.540
And what that does is it's used to quantify how much I'm extrapolating from my training

00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:00.540
set.

00:08:00.540 --> 00:08:04.459
So you can use applicable to have a score that gives you a sense of, like, how far out

00:08:04.459 --> 00:08:07.420
am I or am I sort of, like, in the middle of my training set.

00:08:07.420 --> 00:08:13.260
And they're probably not great for small sample sizes, for some, like, definition of small.

00:08:13.260 --> 00:08:16.980
You can get probably intervals, but, you know, it's hard to say what the coverage would be.

00:08:16.980 --> 00:08:17.980
Okay?

00:08:17.980 --> 00:08:20.559
So I'm going to show you some code.

00:08:20.579 --> 00:08:23.959
So I'm going to have a training set that is 1,000 data points, a test set that's 500,

00:08:23.959 --> 00:08:30.079
and a calibration set, which is where we compute those residuals, about the same size of 500.

00:08:30.079 --> 00:08:34.359
So you can load the TinyModels package down here, and we're going to be looking at some

00:08:34.359 --> 00:08:37.520
results if you use cross-validation, like V4 cross-validation.

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:45.799
So I generated a cross-validation object here using TinyModels.

00:08:45.799 --> 00:08:50.080
The model I'm going to use, which doesn't ordinarily generate prediction intervals,

00:08:50.599 --> 00:08:51.599
is called a support vector machine.

00:08:51.599 --> 00:08:53.960
And here's some code to specify the model.

00:08:53.960 --> 00:08:57.799
And then line seven here is we just fit that support vector machine model.

00:08:57.799 --> 00:09:02.080
And we can use that to generate the curve on that, or the curve on that data point or

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:03.080
data set that I showed you.

00:09:03.080 --> 00:09:04.080
All right.

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:07.559
So there's three different conformal methods I'll go through really quickly.

00:09:07.559 --> 00:09:10.520
The first one's called split conformal inference, and you've already seen it.

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:14.479
So it's basically you take a model, you fit it to your training set, you predict your

00:09:14.479 --> 00:09:18.960
calibration set, compute the residuals, and go on your merry way.

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:21.520
So it's pretty simple.

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:24.599
In TinyModels, you load that with the probability package.

00:09:24.599 --> 00:09:27.460
The functions we're going to show start with int conformal.

00:09:27.460 --> 00:09:30.280
So in the last bit here is the method.

00:09:30.280 --> 00:09:33.419
So what you do is you give it your fit in your calibration set.

00:09:33.419 --> 00:09:36.479
It basically predicts the calibration set, gets residuals.

00:09:36.479 --> 00:09:41.219
And then when you want to actually get the prediction, predictive intervals on new samples,

00:09:41.219 --> 00:09:42.479
you give it, let's say, the test set.

00:09:42.479 --> 00:09:45.479
And here you specify whatever confidence level you want.

00:09:45.479 --> 00:09:50.039
And then you can see you get new columns here, pred lower and pred upper.

00:09:50.039 --> 00:09:55.039
What does that look like for the data set that we just used?

00:09:55.039 --> 00:10:00.400
Is this, again, purple line is our, in this case, support vector machine model prediction.

00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:02.359
And then here's our prediction intervals.

00:10:02.359 --> 00:10:06.840
You see some of them down here aren't really overlapping and so on.

00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:10.159
So as you might imagine, it's pretty fast, pretty simple.

00:10:10.159 --> 00:10:15.059
Again, one of the downsides to it is the interval widths are always the same.

00:10:15.059 --> 00:10:20.859
So whether the variability in your outcome data is really small or really large at different

00:10:20.859 --> 00:10:24.820
points, it's always going to be the same width.

00:10:24.820 --> 00:10:27.859
The downside also to this is you have to have an extra set of data laying around that you

00:10:27.859 --> 00:10:30.380
can use to estimate that distribution.

00:10:30.380 --> 00:10:31.380
We don't always have that.

00:10:31.380 --> 00:10:34.619
So one thing you can do is you can use cross-validation.

00:10:34.619 --> 00:10:38.260
Every time you do cross-validation, you have some data that you're predicting.

00:10:38.260 --> 00:10:44.299
And those data points were not used by the corresponding model that generated the data

00:10:44.539 --> 00:10:47.020
So the data you use for prediction is not the same data you use to fit the model inside

00:10:47.020 --> 00:10:48.020
a cross-validation.

00:10:48.020 --> 00:10:51.820
So if you do tenfold cross-validation, you have ten sets of sort of held-out residuals.

00:10:51.820 --> 00:10:56.780
And it turns out there's some math behind this that says, yeah, you can, with some slight

00:10:56.780 --> 00:11:01.179
alterations, you can do something very simple to split conformal inference.

00:11:01.179 --> 00:11:06.700
The theory has only really been done for default cross-validation.

00:11:06.700 --> 00:11:10.739
So you can use other resampling methods and tiny models to do this, but you sort of get

00:11:10.739 --> 00:11:13.059
a warning that's saying, like, you're at your own risk.

00:11:13.299 --> 00:11:17.820
I have a link near the end of a GitHub repo where I've done a ton of simulations.

00:11:17.820 --> 00:11:20.539
And I did try bootstrapping with this, and it seemed to work pretty well.

00:11:20.539 --> 00:11:26.580
So no guarantees, but it doesn't seem like a horrible idea to try other resampling methods.

00:11:26.580 --> 00:11:30.859
So how that works is a little bit different than what you would normally do with resampling.

00:11:30.859 --> 00:11:34.020
In your control object, you have to save the out-of-sample predictions.

00:11:34.020 --> 00:11:35.440
That's not very exotic.

00:11:35.440 --> 00:11:39.179
But the other thing you do is, if you're doing tenfold cross-validation, you need to save

00:11:39.179 --> 00:11:42.979
the ten fitted models that you generated during cross-validation.

00:11:42.979 --> 00:11:46.419
So the easiest way to do that is there's an argument called extract, and just give

00:11:46.419 --> 00:11:51.099
it the identity function, which just returns itself.

00:11:51.099 --> 00:11:54.140
Then you use the fit resamples function like you normally would.

00:11:54.140 --> 00:11:58.900
And then the inconformal CV function just processes all that data, and this is the same

00:11:58.900 --> 00:12:02.380
thing as it was last time to generate the intervals.

00:12:02.380 --> 00:12:06.739
And so, again, on that same data set, in this particular case, it's not always like this.

00:12:06.739 --> 00:12:10.020
These intervals are very, very close to the split intervals.

00:12:10.020 --> 00:12:14.859
That's not always the case, but it's what happened here.

00:12:14.859 --> 00:12:21.219
Also one little note about this I found with very small sample sizes, when CV plus conformal

00:12:21.219 --> 00:12:26.059
methods center their interval, they center it on the average prediction of the ten cross-validated

00:12:26.059 --> 00:12:29.539
models, not the actual model that you fit on the training set.

00:12:29.539 --> 00:12:33.299
So if you have a very small sample size, those two things might be different, and your intervals

00:12:33.299 --> 00:12:36.219
might be kind of shifted in some places.

00:12:36.219 --> 00:12:42.059
I might try to fix that if you can fix it, but it's just like a little note.

00:12:42.059 --> 00:12:45.500
And then the third and final method, which is very different than the others, is called

00:12:45.500 --> 00:12:47.900
conformalized quantile regression.

00:12:47.900 --> 00:12:52.700
So quantile regression is a pretty well-known in statistics technique where when you fit

00:12:52.700 --> 00:12:57.659
a linear regression and you get a prediction, that's the mean of the outcome distribution.

00:12:57.659 --> 00:13:01.940
And in a quantile regression, like a quantile linear regression, what you can do is you

00:13:01.940 --> 00:13:04.659
can actually make predictions on whatever quantile you want.

00:13:04.659 --> 00:13:07.739
So if you want to do something around the center of the distribution, you would use

00:13:07.739 --> 00:13:14.700
a quantile regression with a 50% quantile, a 0.5 quantile to get the median prediction.

00:13:14.700 --> 00:13:20.260
But it's really, if we set it to be like, let's say, the 0.05 or the 0.95 quantile,

00:13:20.260 --> 00:13:23.219
that's really what we're trying to do, basically, in conformal inferences.

00:13:23.219 --> 00:13:28.219
We're trying to estimate the boundaries of what our predictive distribution is.

00:13:28.219 --> 00:13:32.900
And so it's really a more direct approach to solving this.

00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:36.859
This is the same data set I showed in that second slide where I had linear regression.

00:13:36.859 --> 00:13:41.460
And you can see, maybe, it might be hard to see, but you can see these are not equally spaced.

00:13:41.460 --> 00:13:46.780
So the upside to conformal inference using quantile regression is that you very well

00:13:46.780 --> 00:13:52.099
can get intervals that are not equally spaced like the other two methods.

00:13:52.099 --> 00:13:57.059
Now, linear methods here are maybe not the best of ideas.

00:13:57.059 --> 00:14:00.659
So what we do is what something other people do in the literature is we use a tree-based

00:14:00.700 --> 00:14:04.099
unsolvable, specifically, quantile random forests.

00:14:04.099 --> 00:14:07.020
And then that can give us a prediction interval.

00:14:07.020 --> 00:14:08.380
And here's the same data set.

00:14:08.380 --> 00:14:12.260
You can see, for lack of a better term, I'd call this like a chunky sort of line.

00:14:12.260 --> 00:14:18.140
But it will vary across the range if the variance changes across the range.

00:14:18.140 --> 00:14:21.260
The other thing to note here is you can see when the data stops,

00:14:21.260 --> 00:14:24.299
this is true of all tree-based methods, not just random forest,

00:14:24.299 --> 00:14:28.500
that it just sort of goes off to infinity with the same lines.

00:14:28.500 --> 00:14:31.419
And this is especially bad if you start extrapolating.

00:14:31.419 --> 00:14:34.979
So you can imagine if I set a linear regression to this or something for

00:14:34.979 --> 00:14:38.059
this particular data set, like this cloud of points,

00:14:38.059 --> 00:14:40.539
you can imagine that line just keep increasing.

00:14:40.539 --> 00:14:46.059
But the conformalized quantum intervals will just keep going off in one direction.

00:14:46.059 --> 00:14:49.940
So you can extrapolate and get very, you can get intervals that are so

00:14:49.940 --> 00:14:52.500
poor that they don't even contain the predicted value.

00:14:52.500 --> 00:14:53.940
So just with this particular method,

00:14:53.940 --> 00:14:56.820
especially, you have to be very sure you're not extrapolating.

00:14:57.140 --> 00:15:00.500
All right. The code's a little bit different for this one.

00:15:00.500 --> 00:15:02.659
You need to give it your model fit,

00:15:02.659 --> 00:15:06.340
and you need to give it both the training set and the calibration set.

00:15:06.340 --> 00:15:08.780
So it works best with a split sample.

00:15:08.780 --> 00:15:11.140
And also, since you're estimating the quantiles,

00:15:11.140 --> 00:15:13.260
you have to get the confidence level upfront.

00:15:13.260 --> 00:15:15.859
So instead of setting it in the predict method,

00:15:15.859 --> 00:15:17.460
you have to do it here.

00:15:17.460 --> 00:15:23.340
And then we use the QRF function for quantile regression forests.

00:15:23.380 --> 00:15:24.900
So you have to tell it how many,

00:15:24.900 --> 00:15:27.940
anything you want to pass to that argument or that function,

00:15:27.940 --> 00:15:31.219
you can do it here. So I'm going to bump up the number of trees to 2,000.

00:15:31.219 --> 00:15:33.020
And then they get the actual intervals.

00:15:33.020 --> 00:15:36.340
You just, it's a little bit more simplistic.

00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:39.539
What's that look like for our data set again?

00:15:39.539 --> 00:15:42.820
It's kind of interesting. This seems like you might be like,

00:15:42.820 --> 00:15:45.099
wow, I don't know, that's kind of scary.

00:15:45.099 --> 00:15:47.700
But performance of this is actually pretty good

00:15:47.700 --> 00:15:50.940
despite the lack of smoothness of these intervals.

00:15:50.940 --> 00:15:53.700
So when you do simulations and things like this,

00:15:53.700 --> 00:15:56.539
the idea that you're getting step functions

00:15:56.539 --> 00:16:00.460
across a range is not that big of a deal, performance-wise.

00:16:00.460 --> 00:16:04.380
Speaking of performance, we have to make sure it works.

00:16:04.380 --> 00:16:05.419
So this is a little bit different than

00:16:05.419 --> 00:16:07.820
your average machine learning method because we're saying,

00:16:07.820 --> 00:16:09.820
if you get intervals from this function,

00:16:09.820 --> 00:16:12.619
we think they'll have, let's say, 90 percent coverage.

00:16:12.619 --> 00:16:15.460
And so with this GitHub repo here,

00:16:15.460 --> 00:16:17.260
I did a bunch of simulations to make sure

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:19.539
these things actually work the way they're supposed to work.

00:16:19.739 --> 00:16:22.940
Now, for the data sets I showed you, like this one,

00:16:22.940 --> 00:16:25.419
the coverages were very close to 90 percent.

00:16:25.419 --> 00:16:28.299
So for the original split conformal plot,

00:16:28.299 --> 00:16:30.979
it was just about, CV plus was 80 percent,

00:16:30.979 --> 00:16:32.739
and then we're very close to 90 percent

00:16:32.739 --> 00:16:34.619
for those individual data sets.

00:16:34.619 --> 00:16:38.140
And I have a read me at that repo.

00:16:38.140 --> 00:16:40.219
Generally speaking, I tried it with trees

00:16:40.219 --> 00:16:42.460
and regression and neural networks and things like that.

00:16:42.460 --> 00:16:44.140
The sample size matters a lot.

00:16:44.140 --> 00:16:46.940
So your coverage may not be spectacular

00:16:46.940 --> 00:16:48.380
if you have a very small sample size,

00:16:48.380 --> 00:16:49.700
but I was pretty happy with

00:16:49.700 --> 00:16:52.179
the average coverage of those methods.

00:16:52.179 --> 00:16:53.380
So they seem to be working and doing

00:16:53.380 --> 00:16:56.260
what they're supposed to do.

00:16:56.260 --> 00:16:57.260
So what's next?

00:16:57.260 --> 00:16:59.820
As I mentioned, we've already implemented regression models.

00:16:59.820 --> 00:17:01.260
So probably sometime in the new year,

00:17:01.260 --> 00:17:02.659
I'll start looking at doing the same thing

00:17:02.659 --> 00:17:04.780
for classification models.

00:17:04.780 --> 00:17:08.020
In classification, in this particular domain,

00:17:08.020 --> 00:17:10.420
they typically are focusing on situations

00:17:10.420 --> 00:17:12.900
where we have a lot of classes.

00:17:12.900 --> 00:17:15.459
So let's say you're doing some sort of image classification

00:17:15.500 --> 00:17:18.420
and there's like 30 things you might classify an image as.

00:17:18.420 --> 00:17:20.300
What they focus on with conformal inference

00:17:20.300 --> 00:17:21.939
is saying, like clustering them,

00:17:21.939 --> 00:17:22.979
and saying like, well, you know,

00:17:22.979 --> 00:17:26.500
what is it, like dog or hot dog, that whole thing?

00:17:26.500 --> 00:17:28.020
You know, if you have a prediction

00:17:28.020 --> 00:17:30.699
and you have two class probabilities that are pretty close,

00:17:30.699 --> 00:17:32.380
one thing conformal inference does for you

00:17:32.380 --> 00:17:33.900
is to tell you whether they're like

00:17:33.900 --> 00:17:36.660
sort of equivocal probabilities or not.

00:17:36.660 --> 00:17:38.180
And again, it's a fastly growing field,

00:17:38.180 --> 00:17:40.699
so if there's a new methodology that pops up,

00:17:40.699 --> 00:17:43.099
we will definitely take a look at it.

