And Joe Rickard did a lot of reading

00:17:52.140 --> 00:17:55.020
and help with me on this to get a sense

00:17:55.020 --> 00:17:57.219
of how these things actually work.

00:17:57.219 --> 00:17:59.300
Speaking of which, if you want to learn more,

00:17:59.300 --> 00:18:01.420
there's an article on tinymodels.org.

00:18:01.420 --> 00:18:03.939
The two references I would really suggest the most here

00:18:03.939 --> 00:18:07.500
is Christopher Molinar made this book.

00:18:07.500 --> 00:18:09.260
It says conformal inference with Python,

00:18:09.260 --> 00:18:11.339
but this is probably the best reference

00:18:11.339 --> 00:18:13.979
if you want to get like a layman sense

00:18:13.979 --> 00:18:15.420
of like how these things are working.

00:18:15.420 --> 00:18:18.459
So it's an excellent book, you can get it off Amazon.

00:18:18.459 --> 00:18:21.300
If you're more of the statistical kind of person,

00:18:21.300 --> 00:18:23.500
Ryan Timshirani has a really nice set of notes

00:18:23.500 --> 00:18:25.900
on the various methods and how they work.

00:18:25.900 --> 00:18:28.420
And then there's awesome conformal prediction repo

00:18:28.420 --> 00:18:32.739
and GitHub has like any reference that comes up ever.

00:18:32.739 --> 00:18:33.900
They'll pretty much list it

00:18:33.900 --> 00:18:36.300
in probably this talk or whatever there.

