00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:53.199
Can these be used for anomaly detection in deployed models

00:19:53.199 --> 00:19:55.520
and then drive some sort of emergency action

00:19:55.520 --> 00:19:57.119
to avoid anomalous predictions?

00:19:57.119 --> 00:19:59.119
Yeah, that's a good question.

00:19:59.119 --> 00:20:04.119
So I've seen people on social media say that.

00:20:05.280 --> 00:20:07.719
I don't know that I would buy into it so much.

00:20:07.719 --> 00:20:08.800
If you were using this,

00:20:08.800 --> 00:20:10.739
you could look at the width of the interval

00:20:10.739 --> 00:20:13.040
to get a sense of how it's going

00:20:13.880 --> 00:20:16.520
within the mainstream of your training data.

00:20:16.520 --> 00:20:19.160
So as long as you stay within your training data,

00:20:19.160 --> 00:20:20.000
you're fine.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:23.180
And actually, it wouldn't be very good at all

00:20:23.180 --> 00:20:24.760
for anomaly detection for something

00:20:24.760 --> 00:20:26.640
that's an aberration because it's extrapolation

00:20:26.640 --> 00:20:30.040
because look what happens as you go a little bit further.

00:20:30.040 --> 00:20:32.160
It's like, boop, these goes off into infinity

00:20:32.160 --> 00:20:34.640
and actually my fitted curve goes out here.

00:20:34.640 --> 00:20:37.079
So this is the one you would probably use

00:20:37.079 --> 00:20:38.380
if you want to judge the uncertainty

00:20:38.380 --> 00:20:39.640
by the confidence interval width

00:20:39.640 --> 00:20:42.079
because the other two methods have a fixed width.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:44.939
And it only would really detect anomalies

00:20:44.939 --> 00:20:48.000
that are sort of where your data already live.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:50.479
So that's my answer to that question.

